		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">Bregalad wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">As far I know, fonts are not copyrightable, so logically sound fonts would follow the same rule.<br /></div>Fonts are not copyrightable <em>in the US</em>. In the UK, and Ireland they are. In much of the EU they're covered by design patents.<br /><br />In any case, it's not clear that soundfonts necessarily follow the same rule. In the manual for my old synthesizer, I think I remember finding an explicit licensing clause allowing the use of the samples for commercial products without separate royalties, and AIUI something equivalent is very common in the EULA of most commercial softsynths (You're buying a royalty-free license, not just the software). Conversely, this is part of why CreativeCommons-Sampling license was formed, because this surface wasn't explicitly clear in legal code nor in case law.

		

